ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: 1. Is shy/hesitant when meeting new children
2. Finds schedule changes more difficult than peers (e.g., difficultly adjusting to school transition, changes at home or in the family)
3. Gets frustrated when s/he cant seem to get it right the first time (e.g., when a solving a puzzle, when completing a math problem)
4. Gets upset or has trouble when plans change at short notice
5. Is self-controlled and able to delay gratification
6. Frequently compares his/her abilities with that of peers and siblings
7. Often thinks there is only one right way to do things
8. Has difficulty taking suggestions or receiving help from parents or peers
9. Does better when things are structured and planned out
10. Is concerned with doing things just right (e.g., hair parted the right way, food on plate certain way)
11. Always follows the rules
12. Often checks and double checks work to make sure s/he did not make a mistake
13. Is quiet and uncertain in new situations
14. Wants things done his/her own way (i.e., wants to play his/her way, wants to make the rules)
15. Looks for reassurance that s/he has done well or done the right thing more than siblings or other kids his/her age
16. Becomes upset if things dont go how s/he thinks they should
17. Pays a lot of attention to how s/he does things compared with others
18. Becomes upset when s/he thinks s/he has done poorly on something
19. Becomes very upset if criticized or given suggestions on how to do things differently
20. Is easy-going and flexible
21. Gets mad at him/herself when s/he makes a mistake, especially in front of others
22. Likes being the center of attention
23. Is rigid in his/her way of doing things
24. Becomes upset when others dont follow the rules
25. Often feels not good enough compared with peers or siblings
OCYC Inflexibility/Frustration Subscale
OCYC Social Concern/Perfectionism Subscale
OCYC Behavioral inhibition Subscale
OCYC Total
Respondent
Notes: 1 = Parent; 2 = Teacher; 3=Self; 4= Other; 5= Significant other; 6 = Parent 1; 7 = Parent 2; 999 = Not available
